This one will be pretty difficult to explain ðŸ˜…. In the 90s in France there were very famous tv commercials, for a brand of mint sweets called "kiss cool", whose headline was "le double effet kiss cool" (kiss cool's double effect). They were so famous that, even 20 years later, the expression is still used sometimes in popular language. Now that you have the reference, I made a pun from this expression: I replace the brand name by "qui coule", meaning dripping or flow, and sounding very close. So the caption is a reference to the commercial's famous expression, but it means "the dripping double effect". Got it?
This caption sounds exactly like "avalanche" (same word in French) but is a mix between "avale" ( swallow) and "hanches" (meaning hips). So it could mean "the hips swallower"

I kept the content of the book a little bit secret until now, so here is a small preview of the 50 accounts with the beautiful story of Morgane, from Nantes. I find this story very cute, funny and tender, and I was very touched that Morgane gave me her approval to put it in the book. I was even more touched when I saw Morgane coming to me, during a book signing in Nantes, to thank me and to give me this very touching present: a candle, wrapped in a small note tied with a black ribbon, in remembrance of her Lover at that time, who passed away since then. This is the kind of story I could not hope to live when I launched "petites luxures" by accident 5 years ago! (And please be patient for the translation of the book in other languages, several different versions will be available during 2020, promise!)

"Fesses" means butt. "Face" sounds quite close to fesses, and "en face" means here "across the street". So it's simply a vague alliteration to talk about a butt going across the street.

There is a French expression that does not seem to have an English equivalent, "unique au monde". Literally it means "unique in the world", but I guess that a more usual expression would be something like "the only one of her kind in the world"? Anyway, it makes references to the world, and to the fact of being unique. And for this caption, I just added a "c" before "unique" to make an hybrid word sounding like the beginning of cunnilingus. ðŸŒðŸ‘…ðŸ’•

This one is a wordplay with the French title of Tennessee Williams' play, "Cat on a hot tin roof". In French, the novel is titled "La chatte sur un toit brÃ»lant" (which could be literally translated by something more like "the female cat on a burning hot roof"). "Chatte" (female cat) is also the slang for pussy. I simply removed the last "t" of "toit" (roof) to turn it into "toi", meaning "you". So, to make it short, the caption of this drawing sounds exactly like Tennessee Williams' play title, but means "the pussy on burning hot you".
(And yes, I tried new things with walnut ink and a brush on a different paper)

Caption is a pun coming from the expression "la main dans la main", which means "hand in hand". I simply replaced the first "la main" (the hand) by "l'amant", sounding very close but meaning "the lover". So it sounds almost like "hand it hand" but means "the lover in hand".

The french expression "les deux font la paire" literally means "the two of them make the pair", I think the English equivalent would be "the perfect pair". For this caption, I replaced "paire" by "perle", which means pearl and sounds quite close. So the caption is a variation of the "perfect pair" usual expression, but means "the two of them make the pearl". (And, well, I guess I don't need to explain you the visual analogy of the pearl... do I? ðŸ˜)ðŸ˜˜
